  "text": "## LLVM SelectionDAG Type Expansion Analysis\n\n### Overview\nThe assertion error related to type expansion in LLVM's SelectionDAG legalization process is found in the type legalization infrastructure. While the exact error message 'Cannot expand this type; LLVM lacks the right hooks' was not located verbatim in this repository snapshot, the equivalent error handling is found in the type expansion functions.\n\n### Key Files and Components\n\n#### 1. Type Legalization Entry Point\n**File**: `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.h` (line 31)\n- **Class**: `DAGTypeLegalizer` - The main orchestrator of type legalization\n- This class processes SelectionDAG nodes and transforms illegal types into legal ones\n- Defines the public `run()` method that starts the type legalization process\n\n#### 2. Integer Type Expansion\n**File**: `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeIntegerTypes.cpp` (line 3024)\n- **Function**: `void DAGTypeLegalizer::ExpandIntegerResult(SDNode *N, unsigned ResNo)`\n- This function handles expansion of integer result types\n- When a type needs to be expanded but no handler exists for the specific operation, it reports: \"Do not know how to expand the result of this operator!\" (lines 3039-3040)\n- The function first attempts custom lowering via `CustomLowerNode()`, then uses a switch statement on operation codes to handle specific operations\n\n#### 3. Float Type Expansion  \n**File**: `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeFloatTypes.cpp` (line 1567)\n- **Function**: `void DAGTypeLegalizer::ExpandFloatResult(SDNode *N, unsigned ResNo)`\n- Handles expansion of floating-point result types\n- Reports the same error message: \"Do not know how to expand the result of this operator!\" (lines 1582-1583)\n- Mirrors the structure of `ExpandIntegerResult` for float types\n\n#### 4. Extended Value Type Definition\n**File**: `llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/ValueTypes.h`\n- **Class**: `EVT` (line 35) - Extended Value Type\n- The `isSimple()` method is defined at line 137-139:\n  ```cpp\n  bool isSimple() const {\n    return V.SimpleTy != MVT::INVALID_SIMPLE_VALUE_TYPE;\n  }\n  ```\n- This method checks if the EVT represents a simple (native) machine value type versus an extended/complex type\n- The EVT class wraps both simple types (MVT) and complex types like arbitrary-width integers\n\n### Type Legalization Flow\n\n1. **DAGTypeLegalizer::run()** (`LegalizeTypes.cpp`) - Main entry point\n   - Walks the SelectionDAG and identifies illegal types\n   - Dispatches to appropriate handler functions based on type action (TypeLegal, TypePromoteInteger, TypeExpandInteger, etc.)\n\n2. **ExpandIntegerResult()** / **ExpandFloatResult()** - Type expansion handlers\n   - Called when a value's type needs expansion (split into multiple legal-sized values)\n   - Uses operation-specific handlers or custom lowering hooks\n   - If no handler exists, fires assertion with \"Do not know how to expand the result of this operator!\"\n\n3. **CustomLowerNode()** - Custom expansion hooks\n   - Checks if target has custom lowering via `TLI.getOperationAction()`\n   - Calls target-specific `ReplaceNodeResults()` if available\n   - Allows targets to provide \"hooks\" for expanding operations\n\n### Error Condition\nThe assertion fires when:\n- A SelectionDAG operation result has a type that requires expansion\n- The operation is not handled by the built-in expansion functions\n- No custom target lowering hooks are registered for that operation\n- Result: \"Do not know how to expand the result of this operator!\"\n\nThis is essentially the type expansion equivalent of having no available hooks or methods to transform the illegal type into legal types."
}
